pr_review_comment_body:
while this works and performance wise only a few would be cutted away (the search may deliver more than limit if exact same items are found - iirc): I don't like the whole code. It returns either a generator or an empty list which is wrong. What about - while at it - writing it like so:

```
    def search(self, query, limit=20):
        catalog_query = self.selectable_filter.criteria.copy()
        catalog_query.update(parse_query(query, self.portal_path))

        if limit and 'sort_limit' not in catalog_query:
            catalog_query['sort_limit'] = limit

        try:            
            for index, brain in enumerate(self.catalog(**catalog_query)):
                if index >= limit:
                    break
                yield self.getTermByBrain(brain, real_value=False)
        except ParseError:
            pass
```

nit: reduce the scope of the `except` block here:

```
try:
    from httpie.plugins import AuthPlugin
except ImportError:
    pass
else:
    class FxABrowserIDPlugin(...):
        ...
```

Update doc:
{
 M2cooord(...): ResolvedJar(classifier='', path/cache_path="a.jar"),
 M2cooord(...): ResolvedJar(classifier='', path/cache_path="b.jar")
}

[Don't use mutable defaults](http://docs.python-guide.org/en/latest/writing/gotchas/), which can lead to surprising behavior later. Instead do

```
def ...(..., extra_kwargs=None):
  extra_kwargs = extra_kwargs or {}
```

Also, consider changing this to a LBYL style, e.g.:

```python
if value:
  return address_decoder(value)
self.fail('Please specify a valid hex-encoded address.')
```

I'd prefer not to special-case for the `hue` value. What about something like the following:

```python
def _sample_from(value, name, center=1, clip_first_on_zero=True):
    if isinstance(value, numbers.Number) and value >= 0:
        value = [center - value, center + value]
    if clip_first_on_zero:
        value[0] = max(value[0], 0)
    factor = random.uniform(value[0], value[1])
```
